    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-01-28T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-01-28T21:00:00-05:00" n="681"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d681">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.6359 Wolfram Ore/72: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Peck</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-01-29T09:00:00+07:00"
                            >January 29, 1940—9 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received January 29—4:53 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>51. Reference Department’s mail instruction 176, September 12, 1939,<note n="39"
                        xml:id="d681fn39">
                        <ref target="frus1939v03#pg_710">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1939, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, p. 710</ref>.</note> wolfram exports.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>The person referred to<note n="40" xml:id="d681fn40">T. F Tsiang, Director
                            of the Political Department of the Chinese Executive Yuan</note> in line
                        9, page 1, of the Embassy’s despatch No. 331, September 22, 1939,<note
                            n="41" xml:id="d681fn41">Not printed</note> informed a member of the
                        staff of the Embassy January 17 that Sino-Soviet relations continued
                        satisfactory, but that some concern was felt by Chinese over the fact <pb
                            facs="0647" n="639" xml:id="pg_639"/> that the British and French were
                        exerting pressure to have the Chinese limit shipments of wolfram to Russia
                        to amounts which would preclude the possibility of reshipment of any to
                        Germany; that Chinese had declined to comply with French request to make
                        shipments to Russia on a “quota” basis; that Chinese preferred to ship to
                        Russia since credits bring ten times the value of goods exported in the form
                        of goods received in exchange whereas sales to French and British bring only
                        the actual value of exports. It seemed likely that French and British would
                        continue to insist on guarantee that no wolfram stocks exported from
                        Indo-China and/or Hong Kong were destined ultimately for Germany, but
                        informant seemed hopeful of a solution which would not affect barter trade
                        with Soviets adversely.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>It was learned from the British Embassy on January 26 that the British
                        have proposed to the French and American Governments a plan whereby the
                        three countries would purchase the entire production of wolfram.</item>
                </list>
                <p>Repeated to Peiping, Hong Kong, Shanghai. Hong Kong please inform Hanoi.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Peck</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
